Setting Up the AWS Architecture
I started by setting up the AWS architecture. One of the first issues I ran into was a connection timeout, which I resolved by checking the inbound rules in the wordpress-sg security group and reconfiguring them correctly.

Bash Provisioning Script
After the AWS setup I moved on to writing the bash provisioning script, following the steps from the previous docker class documentation. Some issues I encountered here:

I had trouble with the logic for setting up the configuration, which led me to write an if/else statement to handle both the Dockerfile and docker-compose file scenarios
I forgot to update the program after installing it, which caused issues, learned that the hard way 
I discovered a useful command: bash -n provision.sh which checks for syntax errors in a bash script without actually running it

After running the provision script I hit a curl (28) error. After some research I found out it was likely a routing issue so I tried pinging — that didn't work either. I then headed to AWS Console → VPC → Route Table and discovered there was no subnet association attached to my router. I fixed that by going to the subnet association tab and attaching it to the one bearing my VPC.
It still didn't work after that. More research revealed that the Docker download section needed HTTPS port access which I hadn't included in my security group. After adding that, the provision script worked perfectly.

Connecting to the Instance Locally
I had issues connecting my AWS setup to my local device via terminal. I had directly copied the SSH command without changing the filename and address, which gave me permission and access errors. Once I corrected the file name and target address it connected successfully.

Setting Up .env and docker-compose.yml
This was the most troublesome part of the project. I wanted to set up the environment in VS Code for easy editing and configuration, so I created the files inside a folder called wordpress-pro.

The .env file has four lines and contains the MySQL structure that the Docker containers connect to
The docker-compose.yml file allows the two containers which are MySQL and WordPress and allow them to communicate with each other


EBS Volume
The EBS volume was used for the MySQL database instead of container storage because it acts as a persistent disk where the data lives, mounted directly on the EC2 instance. This means if the instance is restarted or stopped, the data remains intact.

Security Group Configuration
I added the following inbound rules:

SSH — to allow me to configure the instance from my terminal
HTTP — to allow WordPress to be accessed from a browser
HTTPS — to allow Docker to be installed online via the provision script (not explicitly required by the task but added because of the Docker installation step)

There are no security risks with my current port configuration.

Fault Tolerance & Scalability

If the EC2 instance were to crash, the data would still be intact because of the EBS volume mounted to it
If the application needed to handle 100x more users, the best solution would be a load balancer, it acts as an intermediary between the user and the server, stopping traffic from being sent to a crashed server and routing it to other active and stable ones instead


